Brenda's is a place you go to for special occasions or a place to go to show visiting friends. But, I don't think it's a place I would frequent on a regular basis. Brenda's is the place to go for brunch and I've been here during both mornings and night times. I feel that night time (still crazy busy) isn't the best to go to if you're with friends because the lighting is so dim! Nighttime would be better for a date night. Weekday mornings are definitely the times to go if you want to avoid the crazy wait times and crowds. When I went at night (Friday) before, I waited for 1.5 hours for two people. When I went noontime (Monday), no wait at all and plenty of space. PARKING: Street parking only! INTERIOR: The restaurant is split up into two parts. I would say enough room for about 16-20 tables/groups of people. If you come during a wait, they put your party name on a chalkboard (with a warning that wait time is only an estimate). Nighttime is very dim, cozy, ideal for intimate dinners. Brunchtime is much better and brighter (for you food photographers out there). It's not formal attire, but the tables are glass and tablecloth. Cute coffee canisters to hold their utensils. The decorations are used to emulate the Nola vibes. FOOD: + CRAWFISH BEIGNETS: A fun take on beignets. This is the showstopper most people order when it's their first time. It's dusted with cayenne (not very spicy, so don't worry) and filled with crawfish tails and cheese sauce. Unlike your typical light, airy, and fluffy sweet beignets, this is more doughy and chewy. I'm guessing it's to hold the filling inside. I will say that the amount of filling has gotten smaller over the years and it's more bread than crawfish now. Used to be two giant ones, now it's currently three small ones. It's good, but not amazing. + CHICKEN ETOUFEE: Classic cajun dish with chicken instead of the typical shrimp. If Cajun and Creole food had their own type of curry, this would be it. Simple, but powerful flavors. Not too salty. Maybe a little bit basic, but it's good comfort food. Comes with toasted bread and rice. + MUFFALETTA: Ordered with a half and half side of fries and coleslaw. The fries slap. Very surprised that these fries are so dang good. It's crispy (not crunchy) on the outside with soft fluffy potato goodness. The muffaletta sandwich was so decadent and flavorful. The best of both Itialian and Creole cuisine in a sandwich. So much gooey cheese and rich meats. Stay away if you don't like olives. + BFC: As a lover of fried chicken, I had to get an order of Brenda's fried chicken. The fried chicken is okay. I don't think for the quality of this dish that the price is warranted. The fried chicken didn't blow me away. No interesting flavors. It comes with typical sides. [PASS] + SHRIMP & GRITS: I'm not the biggest shrimp person (bad childhood experience with spoiled shrimp). So I only sampled it from my friend's dish. So flavorful. The shrimp is juicy and the tomato-bacon gravy on top is decadent. It pairs so nicely with the cheese-y grits underneath. I can't say I'm an expert on good Southern grits, but Brenda's grits are so good. Again, I will say that I don't think it's a very spicy dish. +GUAVA MIMOSA: Get one for brunch! The champagne is strong and the guava flavor is refreshing. Nice change from the typical orange juice. PRICE: Expensive, but won't break the bank. I find it to be typical of SF food in this part of Tenderloin. Each main dish ranges from $14-17. So a complete meal here will be about $20. Overall: Would come here for special occasions because the wait is not worth it and the abundance of brunch places in SF won't leave you feeling crushed if you can't make it here. If you're able to snag Brenda's at a not-so-busy time, I would say it's worth a try.

Didn't see much of the "French" but there is plenty of "Soul" here! My party and I split the fried cauliflower and opted for the beignet platter to start and I ended up ordering the Andouille Sausage Jambalaya with Green Salad. Fried Cauliflower: The cauliflower itself didn't blow me away but the creamy cilantro dipping sauce was great! This can definitely be used as a salad dressing too. Beignet Platter: There were four beignets: crawfish, apple, chocolate, and original. For the apple beignet, it reminded me of a lot like apple pie. The chocolate one was decadent and the original was a classic. All beignets were crispy and fluffy- the way beignets should be! But lets talk about them crawfish beignets! WOW, so delicious. They didn't skimp out on the crawfish meat and it was seasoned well with various Creole spices. It was also slightly creamy inside? I was glad the filling balanced out with the crispiness of the the beignet. Andouille Sausage Jambalaya: This jambalaya was actually not as "saucy" as what I am used to but it wasn't dry which was great. The rice did pack a punch but it was a little bit salt overboard on this dish. Green Salad: This salad was a bit of a flop for me. It was pretty plain with just your average iceberg lettuce and some slices of red onion. It would've been nice to have some cherry tomatoes, cheese, etc. to dress it up a bit. The shallot vinaigrette was okay for me. Not my favorite but it was decent. Overall the meal was wonderful! Luckily on New Year's night, this place wasn't as packed compared to a weekday at lunch. The decorations were great with the Christmas garland and lights up. Our server was decent, not exceptional. She seemed to be a little unknowledgeable about the components of the dish and didn't seem very enthusiastic during her shift.

I didn't mind because that also reminded me of my brief time in New Orleans. Though it can be loud inside, it actually wasn't too noticeable. I was able to have a conversation without yelling. Our waiter was super nice, and our food came out quick! Like within 10 minutes of ordering and it was hot, so it wasn't like they were making it too ahead of time. Brenda's is one of the best places to eat in the Tenderloin. I've eaten here for over 6 years, and nothing has disappointed me. I want to come back to try their Hangtown fry!

    3/11/2020

    Brenda's is a place you go to for special occasions or a place to go to show visiting friends. But, I don't think it's a place I would frequent on a regular basis. Brenda's is the place to go for brunch and I've been here during both mornings and night times. I feel that night time (still crazy busy) isn't the best to go to if you're with friends because the lighting is so dim! Nighttime would be better for a date night. Weekday mornings are definitely the times to go if you want to avoid the crazy wait times and crowds. When I went at night (Friday) before, I waited for 1.5 hours for two people. When I went noontime (Monday), no wait at all and plenty of space.

    PARKING: Street parking only!

    INTERIOR: The restaurant is split up into two parts. I would say enough room for about 16-20 tables/groups of people. If you come during a wait, they put your party name on a chalkboard (with a warning that wait time is only an estimate). Nighttime is very dim, cozy, ideal for intimate dinners. Brunchtime is much better and brighter (for you food photographers out there). It's not formal attire, but the tables are glass and tablecloth. Cute coffee canisters to hold their utensils. The decorations are used to emulate the Nola vibes.

    FOOD:

    + CRAWFISH BEIGNETS: A fun take on beignets. This is the showstopper most people order when it's their first time. It's dusted with cayenne  (not very spicy, so don't worry) and filled with crawfish tails and cheese sauce. Unlike your typical light, airy, and fluffy sweet beignets, this is more doughy and chewy. I'm guessing it's to hold the filling inside. I will say that the amount of filling has gotten smaller over the years and it's more bread than crawfish now. Used to be two giant ones, now it's currently three small ones. It's good, but not amazing.

    + CHICKEN ETOUFEE: Classic cajun dish with chicken instead of the typical shrimp. If Cajun and Creole food had their own type of curry, this would be it. Simple, but powerful flavors. Not too salty. Maybe a little bit basic, but it's good comfort food. Comes with toasted bread and rice.

    + MUFFALETTA: Ordered with a half and half side of fries and coleslaw. The fries slap. Very surprised that these fries are so dang good. It's crispy (not crunchy) on the outside with soft fluffy potato goodness. The muffaletta sandwich was so decadent and flavorful. The best of both Itialian and Creole cuisine in a sandwich. So much gooey cheese and rich meats. Stay away if you don't like olives.

    + BFC: As a lover of fried chicken, I had to get an order of Brenda's fried chicken. The fried chicken is okay. I don't think for the quality of this dish that the price is warranted. The fried chicken didn't blow me away. No interesting flavors. It comes with typical sides. [PASS]

    + SHRIMP & GRITS: I'm not the biggest shrimp person (bad childhood experience with spoiled shrimp). So I only sampled it from my friend's dish. So flavorful. The shrimp is juicy and the tomato-bacon gravy on top is decadent. It pairs so nicely with the cheese-y grits underneath. I can't say I'm an expert on good Southern grits, but Brenda's grits are so good. Again, I will say that I don't think it's a very spicy dish.

    +GUAVA MIMOSA: Get one for brunch! The champagne is strong and the guava flavor is refreshing. Nice change from the typical orange juice.

    PRICE: Expensive, but won't break the bank. I find it to be typical of SF food in this part of Tenderloin. Each main dish ranges from $14-17. So a complete meal here will be about $20.

    Overall: Would come here for special occasions because the wait is not worth it and the abundance of brunch places in SF won't leave you feeling crushed if you can't make it here. If you're able to snag Brenda's at a not-so-busy time, I would say it's worth a try.

    Didn't see much of the "French" but there is plenty of "Soul" here!

    My party and I split the fried cauliflower and opted for the beignet platter to start and I ended up ordering the Andouille Sausage Jambalaya with Green Salad.

    Fried Cauliflower: The cauliflower itself didn't blow me away but the creamy cilantro dipping sauce was great! This can definitely be used as a salad dressing too.

    Beignet Platter: There were four beignets: crawfish, apple, chocolate, and original. For the apple beignet, it reminded me of a lot like apple pie. The chocolate one was decadent and the original was a classic. All beignets were crispy and fluffy- the way beignets should be! But lets talk about them crawfish beignets! WOW, so delicious. They didn't skimp out on the crawfish meat and it was seasoned well with various Creole spices. It was also slightly creamy inside? I was glad the filling balanced out with the crispiness of the the beignet.

    Andouille Sausage Jambalaya: This jambalaya was actually not as "saucy" as what I am used to but it wasn't dry which was great. The rice did pack a punch but it was a little bit salt overboard on this dish.

    Green Salad: This salad was a bit of a flop for me. It was pretty plain with just your average iceberg lettuce and some slices of red onion. It would've been nice to have some cherry tomatoes, cheese, etc. to dress it up a bit. The shallot vinaigrette was okay for me. Not my favorite but it was decent.

    Overall the meal was wonderful! Luckily on New Year's night, this place wasn't as packed compared to a weekday at lunch. The decorations were great with the Christmas garland and lights up. Our server was decent, not exceptional. She seemed to be a little unknowledgeable about the components of the dish and didn't seem very enthusiastic during her shift.

    Ohhhhhh, mmmmm, ooooooh

    The wait:

    So first thing, you have to write your name on the chalkboard to be seated. We came at 10 am on a Saturday morning and we got sat within 30-40 minutes.

    The food:

    Beignet sampler $12 (original, Granny Smith, chocolate and crawfish) - if you had to choose one I definitely recommend the Granny Smith! It was our favorite and so mouth watering delicious.

    Fried chicken eggs Benedict $15 - This whole meal was everything I dreamed brunch would be. The biscuit was so dense and buttery, the fried chicken was flavorful and crunchy, the eggs cooked perfectly and the Hollandaise sauce delightfully tied everything together. I also ordered the cheese grits as the side and errrmagerd. I am in love!!!

    I docked a star because it was obvious that the kitchen lost our order at some point. It took over 35 minutes for our entrees to come out and all of the other tables that ordered at the same time as us had already finished their food. I wished their staff would've been more honest with the situation rather than just promising that our food "was on its way out" when it clearly wasn't. They tried to make us happy with (1) free cup of gumbo.... but we had 5 people at our table...

    This is definitely a spot you need to try if you love carbs, fat, and some good ole comfort food.

    I finally had the opportunity to eat brunch here, and it did not disappoint!

    My friend from the East Bay drove, and with all the holiday craziness, I suggested to meet around 9:30am. I figured the wait wouldn't be that long. It was maybe 20 minutes, which isn't bad. But seeing a crowd of people already waiting outside got me worried! They only had opened at 8am, but I should've known how popular Brenda's is for brunch.

    I work nearby, so I've only had their lunch options.. though I do recall ordering a scramble to go one work day, but that was a very long time ago. I think it had andouille sausage.. I just remember it being good.

    So it was great to finally eat in.  My friend and I looked at the menu the night before, so we basically knew what we wanted. She got the eggs Benedict with fried chicken and hash, mine with fried catfish and grits. It was so good! The eggs were the most perfect eggs I've ever had! My favorite part of a bene is slicing the egg open to let the yolk out. After slicing, the yolk was still intact, so I had to sorta pop it. It was soooooooo satisfying.

    The hollandaise sauce has a good spice to it, and the biscuit was so creamy! The catfish had a good crunch on the outside, and was flaky on the inside. Biting into the Benedict as a whole was texturally pleasing, as well as flavorful. The grits were very yummy, but I was so full from the Benedict, that I ate it later in the day. It made good leftovers.  

    I also ordered a chicory coffee, and it transported me back to New Orleans.  There's a good amount of seating inside, but it's cramped.  I didn't mind because that also reminded me of my brief time in New Orleans. Though it can be loud inside, it actually wasn't too noticeable. I was able to have a conversation without yelling.

    Our waiter was super nice, and our food came out quick! Like within 10 minutes of ordering and it was hot, so it wasn't like they were making it too ahead of time.

    Brenda's is one of the best places to eat in the Tenderloin. I've eaten here for over 6 years, and nothing has disappointed me. I want to come back to try their Hangtown fry!
